properties.name: Charles A. Dana Discovery Center
properties.describtion: Opened in 1993 and offers Conservancy-sponsored free education and community programs, seasonal exhibits and holiday celebrations.

properties.name: Belvedere Castle
properties.describtion: Calvert Vaux created the miniature castle in 1869 as a whimsical structures intended as a lookout to the reservoir (now the Great Lawn) and the Ramble.

properties.name: Dairy Visitor Center & Gift Shop
properties.describtion: Parkgoers can find information on Park events and programs at the Dairy.

properties.name: Chess & Checkers House
properties.describtion: Chess and Checkers players are welcome to borrow game pieces from Conservancy staff, or bring their own.

properties.name: Information Kiosk
properties.describtion: Get directions, maps and information about Central Park at the Park's three information kiosks.

properties.name: Wien Walk
properties.describtion: Wien Walk is one of the most heavily traveled entrance paths into Central Park at Fifth Avenue and 60th Street.

properties.name: The Pond
properties.describtion: The Pond is one of Central Park's seven naturalistic water bodies.

properties.name: Hallett Nature Sanctuary Hallett Nature Sanctuary
properties.describtion: Surrounded by the Pond at the southeast corner of Central Park is the 4-acre Nature Sanctuary.

properties.name: Cop Cot
properties.describtion: Cop Cot, which may means little cottage on the crest of the hill in Scottish is Central Park's largest wooden rustic structure.

properties.name: Dairy Visitor Center & Gift Shop
properties.describtion: Parkgoers can find information on Park events and programs at the Dairy.

properties.name: Umpire Rock
properties.describtion: One of the best examples of Central Park's exposed bedrock, Umpire Rock is likely named for its commanding view of nearby baseball diamonds.

properties.name: Dene Slope
properties.describtion: The Dene Slope is a 1.25-acre native meadow in the southwest corner of the Dene landscape.

properties.name: Central Park Zoo
properties.describtion: Built when the Wildlife Conservation Society took over Zoo management in 1984.

properties.name: Arsenal
properties.describtion: The Arsenal was built between 1847 -1851 for the New York National Guard.

properties.name: Olmsted Flower Bed
properties.describtion: The flowerbed at the southern end of the Mall was created in 1972 to commemorate the 150th anniversary of Frederick Law Olmsted's birthday.

properties.name: The Mall and Literary Walk
properties.describtion: The Mall is Central Park's most important horticultural feature and one of the last remaining stands of American Elm trees in North America.

properties.name: Dene
properties.describtion: The Dene is a long stretch of eastside landscape that exemplifies the design features and the intended effect of Olmsted's pastoral vision.

properties.name: Nell Singer Lilac Walk
properties.describtion: On the northern edge of Sheep Meadow, Lilac Walk boasts varieties of its signature fragrant flower from around the world.

properties.name: Sheep Meadow
properties.describtion: Central Park’s largest lawn without ballfields, preserved for quiet picnicking and relaxation.

properties.name: Tavern on the Green
properties.describtion: Tavern on the Green restaurant was built in 1870 as the Sheepfold for the flock of sheep who grazed on the adjacent Sheep Meadow.

properties.name: Wisteria Pergola
properties.describtion: Features century-old wisteria vines attached to a wooden shelter that is reminiscent of the original that was designed by Calvert Vaux.

properties.name: East Green
properties.describtion: Visitors in search of a tranquil area to relax on a lawn can head to East Green, one of eight designated Quiet Zones in Central Park.

properties.name: Pilgrim Hill
properties.describtion: The knoll that rises to the southwest of Conservatory Water toped with a bronze statue of a Pilgrim.

properties.name: Bethesda Terrace
properties.describtion: In their original plan, Olmsted and Vaux envisioned a sweeping Promenade (the Mall) that led to a grand terrace overlooking the Lake.

properties.name: Strawberry Fields
properties.describtion: Strawberry Fields is a living memorial to the world-famous singer, songwriter and peace activist, John Lennon.

properties.name: Cherry Hill
properties.describtion: A gentle slope overlooking the Lake with views to the Ramble, Cherry Hill offers a contemplative space perfect for picnicking, reading, and sunbathing.

properties.name: The Point
properties.describtion: The Point is a verdant peninsula in the Ramble that juts into the Lake.

properties.name: Lake Boat Landings
properties.describtion: Learn about the history and reconstruction of the boat landings around the lake.

properties.name: Rustic Overlook
properties.describtion: Just off the bridle path at West 74th Street is an enclave of three rustic benches and fences.

properties.name: Hernshead
properties.describtion: Promontory that juts out into the Lake named after what must have once been the shape of a "hern" a bird often sighted in Central Park.

properties.name: Ladies Pavilion
properties.describtion: Ladies Pavilion is an important and charming example of 19th century American decorative arts.

properties.name: Azalea Walk
properties.describtion: Just south under Eaglevale Arch, Azalea Walk blooms in the springtime with a colorful variety of azaleas and rhododendrons.

properties.name: Bank Rock Bay
properties.describtion: The narrow inlet of water at the northern tip of the Lake, just beyond Oak Bridge.

properties.name: Azalea Pond
properties.describtion: Azalea Pond gets its name from the century-old azalea plants that crown its southern edge

properties.name: Gill
properties.describtion: A tumbling stream that cuts through the Ramble and trickles down a rocky slope before spilling into the Lake.

properties.name: Cedar Hill
properties.describtion: Ideal spot for picnicking, reading and sunbathing, and in winter one of the most popular sledding hills.

properties.name: Iphigene's Walk
properties.describtion: Commemorating the Central Park advocate, preservationist, and philanthropist Iphigene Ochs Sulzberger.

properties.name: Belvedere Castle
properties.describtion: Calvert Vaux created the miniature castle in 1869 as a whimsical structures intended as a lookout to the reservoir (now the Great Lawn) and the Ramble.

properties.name: Vista Rock
properties.describtion: The highest point in Central Park, Vista Rock is a massive outcropping of schist from which Belvedere Castle stands.

properties.name: Turtle Pond
properties.describtion: Like all of the other water bodies in Central Park, Turtle Pond is man-made, filled with New York City drinking water.

properties.name: Conservatory Water
properties.describtion: Popular with families for the climbing sculptures, storytelling programs, model boats, cafe and the site in the children's classic Stuart Little.

properties.name: Shakespeare Garden
properties.describtion: The garden contains flowers and plants mentioned in Shakespeare poems and plays, with small bronze plaques with quotes from the Bard.

properties.name: Naturalists' Walk
properties.describtion: Restored in 1996, this landscape features rustic benches and an inviting meadow and rock outcrop.

properties.name: Delacorte Theater
properties.describtion: The Delacorte Theater is the summer home of the Public Theater.

properties.name: Summit Rock
properties.describtion: At 141.8 feet, Summit Rock is the highest natural elevation in Central Park.

properties.name: Arthur Ross Pinetum
properties.describtion: The Arthur Ross Pinetum is a four-acre landscape that features 17 different species of pine trees.

properties.name: Seneca Village Site
properties.describtion: Seneca Village may possibly have been Manhattan's first stable community of African American property owners.

properties.name: Reservoir
properties.describtion: Built in the 1860s as a temporary water supply for New York City, the Reservoir is surrounded by a 1.58 mile running track.

properties.name: East Meadow
properties.describtion: This pastoral meadow just off of Fifth Avenue is a popular spot for events and recreation.

properties.name: Conservatory Garden
properties.describtion: Six-acre formal garden divided into three smaller gardens, each with a distinct style: Italian, French, and English.

properties.name: The Pool
properties.describtion: With its grassy banks, weeping willows, and rushing waterfall, the Pool is one of the most idyllic spots in the Park.

properties.name: Pool Grotto
properties.describtion: Jutting from the southwest of the Pool, this naturalistic boulder grotto is the well-concealed reminder that Central Park is entirely man-made.

properties.name: The Ravine
properties.describtion: The Ravine, the only stream valley in the Park, is part of a 40-acre woodland called the North Woods.

properties.name: The Loch
properties.describtion: The Loch, Scottish for lake, is partially fed by a natural watercourse, known in the 17th and 18th centuries as Montayne's Rivulet.

properties.name: The Mount
properties.describtion: Today, this area is the site of the Conservancy's composting operation.

properties.name: Fort Fish
properties.describtion: A military fortification built atop the steep bluffs of the Harlem Meer and stands today as an open green field.

properties.name: Blockhouse
properties.describtion: The Blockhouse is the only remaining fortification of the many built in 1814 to defend against the British.

properties.name: North Woods
properties.describtion: Perhaps the most secluded and peaceful area of Central Park offering a taste of the Adirondack Mountains just a few subway stops from Times Square.

properties.name: Nutter's Battery
properties.describtion: A military fortification built atop the steep bluffs of the Harlem Meer, today offers views of Harlem Meer.

properties.name: McGowan's Pass
properties.describtion: McGowan's Pass is one of the fortifications in the northern end of Central Park that had a role in both the American Revolution and War of 1812.

properties.name: Harlem Meer
properties.describtion: Meaning the dutch word for lake, the Meer memorialized the former separate village of Harlem.

properties.name: Fort Clinton
properties.describtion: A military fortification built atop the bluffs overlooking the Harlem Meer that offers stunning views of the water and the surrounding landscape.

properties.name: North Meadow Butterfly Gardens
properties.describtion: The North Meadow Butterfly Gardens were established in 2000 to support butterfly populations, as well as a variety of moths, insects, and birds.

properties.name: Swedish Cottage
properties.describtion: The Swedish Cottage is home to one of the last public marionette companies in the United States. Puppeteers have worked there since 1947.

properties.name: Loeb Boathouse
properties.describtion: At the Loeb Boathouse, visitors can rent rowboats and bikes, hire an authentic Venetian gondola, or dine overlooking views of the Lake.

properties.name: Victorian Gardens Amusement Park
properties.describtion: As the summer operation of Wollman Rink, this whimsical family amusement park features twelve hand-crafted rides that are sure to delight all guests.

properties.describtion: Parkgoers can find information on Park events and programs at the Dairy.
